                <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11/878: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-01-10T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 10, 1923—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. Your 6, January 4, 4 p.m.</p>
                <p>Department feels that it was the clear intent under the Protocol, and so
                    acknowledged by the Chinese Government by exchange of notes of 1905 that the
                    debt should be paid in gold. It would not seem that the fluctuating value of the
                    paper currency of the Protocol powers could be availed of if those powers
                    object. Assuming that the payments will be made in francs, the Governments
                    concerned apparently have the right to insist upon gold francs which, it is
                    understood, have the same gold content now as they had in 1905.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
